{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti Chapter 8 outlines penalties for physical assaults, including threats with limbs or objects interpreted as weapons (such as a stick, akin to a basic weapon). There is no verbatim reference to \"pointing a weapon\" at a Brahmin without using it, but the closest match appears in the rules for assault, where threatening gestures escalate based on the victim's status (Brahmin as the superior varṇa).**\n\nThe text states: \"With whatever limb a low-born man should injure a superior, that very limb of his shall be cut off.\"[^1] Immediately following: \"He who raises his hand or a stick deserves to have his hand cut off; he who strikes in anger with his foot deserves to have his foot cut off.\"[^2]\n\nThis applies in context to assaults on superiors (including Brahmins), as the preceding verse specifies low-born assailants against superiors. Raising a stick—understood as a weapon or rod (*daṇḍa*)—without striking warrants **amputation of the hand**. No lesser penalty (e.g., fine) is listed for this threat alone; actual injury invokes the \"limb-for-limb\" rule.[^1]\n\n**No other passage in Chapter 8 precisely matches \"pointing a weapon\" (no terms like \"aims,\" \"directs,\" or specific weapons like sword/bow appear in threats against Brahmins).** Penalties intensify for Brahmins throughout (e.g., verbal abuse fines higher against them), but threats remain tied to the act described.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [8.279](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-526528).\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, [8.280](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-c0dabc).\n[^3]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 8 overview ([full chapter](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/)).",
